  <!-- Advantages -->
  <h2 id="advantages">Advantages</h2>
  <p>
    Centrifuges offer several benefits over conventional heating and settling of crude oil to separate BS&amp;W. The following is a list of the main advantages of crude oil centrifuges.
  </p>

  <div class="not-prose space-y-3 mb-6">
    <div class="flex gap-3">
      <span class="text-gold font-bold mt-0.5 shrink-0">&#10003;</span>
      <div class="text-text text-sm leading-relaxed">
        <strong class="text-navy">High Throughput:</strong> Centrifuges exert thousands of times the force of gravity, thereby causing instant separation of crude oil from the bottom sediment and water. Traditional settling works under a single force of gravity and takes much longer.
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="flex gap-3">
      <span class="text-gold font-bold mt-0.5 shrink-0">&#10003;</span>
      <div class="text-text text-sm leading-relaxed">
        <strong class="text-navy">Compact Size:</strong> Settling tanks have large footprints and therefore require considerable real estate for deployment. Centrifuges are comparatively much smaller to handle the same volume of oil.
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="flex gap-3">
      <span class="text-gold font-bold mt-0.5 shrink-0">&#10003;</span>
      <div class="text-text text-sm leading-relaxed">
        <strong class="text-navy">Energy Efficient:</strong> Centrifuges process the crude oil continuously. Therefore, they can use inline heating, which heats up only when the oil is separated. Heater treaters heat thousands of barrels of oil which is colossal energy waste.
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="flex gap-3">
      <span class="text-gold font-bold mt-0.5 shrink-0">&#10003;</span>
      <div class="text-text text-sm leading-relaxed">
        <strong class="text-navy">Quick Deployment:</strong> Compared to tank farms with related permitting and land acquisition, the centrifuge can be deployed in a fraction of the time.
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="flex gap-3">
      <span class="text-gold font-bold mt-0.5 shrink-0">&#10003;</span>
      <div class="text-text text-sm leading-relaxed">
        <strong class="text-navy">Less Capital Expense:</strong> Considering the cost of land, tankage, permits, and disposal facilities, the cost of heating and settling is far greater than that of a centrifuge system.
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="flex gap-3">
      <span class="text-gold font-bold mt-0.5 shrink-0">&#10003;</span>
      <div class="text-text text-sm leading-relaxed">
        <strong class="text-navy">Reduced Oil Losses:</strong> It is possible to produce oil with less than 1% BS&amp;W with a centrifuge system with minimal losses. A considerable amount of oil is lost in drained bottoms to achieve similar quality oil.
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="flex gap-3">
      <span class="text-gold font-bold mt-0.5 shrink-0">&#10003;</span>
      <div class="text-text text-sm leading-relaxed">
        <strong class="text-navy">Better Quality Oil:</strong> The high g-force exerted by centrifuges leads to a much higher quality of crude oil when compared to oil produced by simple gravity settling.
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="flex gap-3">
      <span class="text-gold font-bold mt-0.5 shrink-0">&#10003;</span>
      <div class="text-text text-sm leading-relaxed">
        <strong class="text-navy">Reduced Disposal Costs:</strong> A centrifuge-produced dry sludge cake (reduced disposal volume) reduces disposal costs. Conventional tank bottoms contain higher amounts of oil and water, leading to larger disposal volumes.
